{
  "text": "In wild-type nerve terminals, capacitance changes increase roughly linearly with Ca 2+ influx (longer pulses than those employed here saturate exocytosis, see ref. [CITATION_1] . In Syt IV knockouts, the relationship was more complicated. With low Ca 2+ influx, Syt IV knockout nerve terminals showed larger capacitance changes than wild types and the points in the low Ca 2+ -influx region fell along a steep line. At higher Ca 2+ influx, however, this plot was not nearly as steep. A statistical analysis of our data (by k-means clustering, see Methods) revealed two groups of knockout capacitance recordings, each following a distinct linear relationship (Fig. 4b) . In contrast, the wild-type data showed no Figure 3a ,b. Capacitance changes were plotted against Ca 2+ influx (the integral of the Ca 2+ current). The wild-type plot was roughly linear and the entire dataset was fitted to one line. In the knockout plot, capacitance increased steeply with Ca 2+ influx at low Ca 2+ influx, but at high Ca 2+ influx the knockout data fell along a line with a much lower slope. k-means clustering analysis showed two clusters in the knockout plot (KO1 and KO2) (Supplementary Data online and Fig. 1 ). Each cluster was fitted separately to a line (fitting parameters for all three plots are in the figure) . Including the origin in the fits gave essentially the same results. (c) Capacitance changes were compared for Ca 2+ influx o7 pC and 7-30 pC. For the o7 pC group, the recordings from wild-type terminals showed smaller capacitance changes than those from knockout terminals (6.0 \u00b1 0.7 fF (n \u00bc 44) versus 11.0 \u00b1 1.3 fF (n \u00bc 48), respectively). For the 7-30 pC group, the result was reversed (17.4 \u00b1 1.4 fF (n \u00bc 25) versus 12.5 \u00b1 1.2 fF (n \u00bc 21)). * indicates P o 0.001 and P \u00bc 0.004 for the low and high Ca 2+ -entry capacitance changes, respectively. Mean Ca 2+ influxes for o7 pC were 2.1 \u00b1 0.3 pC for wild type and 2.4 \u00b1 0.3 pC for knockout; for the 7-30 pC range, mean Ca 2+ influxes were 13.4 \u00b1 1.1 pC for wild type and 14.5 \u00b1 1.2 pC for knockout. Note that the nerve terminals were similar in size (wild-type capacitance, 5.2 \u00b1 0.8 pF; knockout capacitance, 5.4 \u00b1 0.6; P \u00bc 0.4). Error bars and errors in the legend represent s.e. Figure 3 Voltage-dependent Ca 2+ current in pituitary nerve terminals. (a) Ca 2+ current in a knockout nerve terminal evoked by 200-ms voltage steps from a holding potential of -80 mV to test potentials (-50 to 50 mV in increments of 10 mV). Bathing [Ca 2+ ] was 10 mM for all the experiments of this figure, for both wild type and knockout. Note that, as part of the capacitance measurement protocol, a sine wave (data not shown) was applied to the patch-clamp command potential immediately before and after the voltage steps. Dashed lines indicate the baseline calculated as the leak current at the holding potential of -80 mV. (b) Average peak Ca 2+ current (after leak subtraction) with s.e. plotted versus test potential normalized to the maximum value (at 10 mV). Normalized plots show that the voltage dependence of Ca 2+ current was the same between wild type (n \u00bc 9) and knockout (n \u00bc 9). (c) Maximum Ca 2+ current (at 10 mV) for a given nerve terminal was plotted against whole-terminal capacitance for that nerve terminal (black diamonds, wild type; open squares, knockout). Linear regression yielded an Bthreefold greater slope for wild type than for knockout, and this difference was not affected by constraining the fits to pass through the origin. Inset, mean Ca 2+ -current density (averages of the ratio of peak Ca 2+ current to nerve terminal capacitance with s.e.) was significantly larger in wild type than in knockout (P \u00bc 0.003). The KO2 group resembled wild type, whereas the KO1 group followed a much steeper slope and fell entirely in the low Ca 2+ -influx region. Clustering analysis indicated that wild-type and knockout nerve terminals responded differently to high and low Ca 2+ influx. To explore this difference without using cluster analysis, we took all of the wildtype and knockout data and sorted on the basis of a Ca 2+ influx at either o7 pC or 7-30 pC. In each group, the mean Ca 2+ influxes were similar for wild-type and knockout terminals (P \u00bc 0.24 and 0.21 for low and high Ca 2+ influx, respectively), but the mean capacitance changes differed significantly (P o 0.001 and P \u00bc 0.004 for low and high Ca 2+ -entry, respectively; Fig. 4c ). In the low Ca 2+ -influx region, the mean capacitance change was higher for knockout terminals (wild type: 6.0 \u00b1 0.7 fF, n \u00bc 44; knockout: 11.0 \u00b1 1.3 fF, n \u00bc 48, P o 0.001), whereas the mean capacitance change was higher in wild-type terminals for high Ca 2+ influx (wild type: 17.4 \u00b1 1.4 fF, n \u00bc 25; knockout: 12.5 \u00b1 1.2 fF, n \u00bc 21, P \u00bc 0.004). Thus, in the absence of Syt IV, low Ca 2+ influx produced more exocytosis, but high Ca 2+ influx reversed this trend.",
